At the risk of this becoming a 'Can Not! Can Too!' argument, I'll bite for a moment. Why not? if you are say, a HE but wanted to RP a Troll Enchanter you COULD, simply by saying that your 'natural form' was the illusion. Not that I am suggesting peopl just go out and free-form roleplay whatever they want, but the fact remains they can. Tier'dal can Roleplay Drow, and a Dwarf could Roleplay being an Evil Duergar who worships Lolth even if his character sheet says Brell.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Mostly it would be because Trolls lack the intelligence or education system to become Enchanters.  If you decide to disagree then you destroy a shared assumption I use as a basis for our role-playing within a shared world environment.  Yes, you can role-play whatever you want in the privacy of your own home <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But if you want to play a role-playing GAME then you need to have a shared set of assumptions and guidelines between all players.  Once people start throwing that out then the people who want role-playing in their role-playing game (as opposed to those who don't) lose the common ground needed to successfully share a role-playing experience.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I fail to see the significance? What you roleplay is what you roleplay. If you want to Roleplay a Vampire you can do it however you want. You can Emote being damaged by sunlight. If your character was ACTUALLY a Vampire and was damaged by the sun it wouldn't be roleplaying. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What?!  That's just plain unfathomable.  I can't role-play a vampire if my character is a vampire?  That's crazy.  I've role-played vampires in LARP for years and all of my characters were vampires.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>After all C0unt Draacu1ia who never roleplayed a day in his life who was also playing a Vamp would be burned by the sun too... Game Mechanics do not equal roleplay. In a game like EQ, it is what you MAKE of the Game Mechanics that matters.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes but if you ignore the mechanics and the world you may be role-playing but you are not playing a role-playing game.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
/yawn. What does SONY have to do with Roleplaying? Mind you, I am actually a big fan of &quot;Color within the lines&quot; style of Roleplay. But would you not agree that Roleplay and Rules are two different animals? Yes, the key to fun is in the integration, but you can Roleplay without regard to EQ Rules just as easily as you can Play EQ without Roleplaying.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Lacking a game master I must use Sony's material to define the scope of my role-playing.  Otherwise I could role-play someone who talks in d00d sp33k and has a telepathic link to another realm where I can get sports scores and discuss them IC.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The 'group bug' allowed you to group, but yes, the old rules did force people to tailor their play to a certain style. But are you cognizant of the fact that a Paladin and Shadow Knight could very easily ROLEPLAY that they were best buddies despite not being able to Group or Buff one another?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They could but it would run contrary to the mythos of the world we are supposedly role-playing in.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Do you not see that 'Grouping' is an OOC Concept? Sure, I suppose you could Roleplay that you can enter &quot;Telepathic Union&quot; with up to 5 other people (More now with Raid Function!) and whatnot, but I usually leave stuff like that out of my Roleplay because personally, I find it clumsy and awkward.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Forming a party of adventurers who work together is a fantasy convention that goes back at least as far as Tolkein.  If, for some reason, you can't do this then that should at least be considered in defining your role-playing framework.<br>
<br>
I'm not a big fan of freeform role-playing with no guidelines on the realm.  I've seen too many role-players (outside EQ) who lacked the ability to deal with challenges hide behind the defense that they can &quot;role-play whatever they want&quot;.<br>
